commentBody:
@John Deal
Me too!  First time through I had only REDAPPLE crossing SEDER.  Except I spelled it SEDaR, which gave me REPlayS instead of REPORTS.  I got a few more on second pass.  Went away for a few hours and got almost nothing else.  Then I started using my favorite search engine to look up the POETs, researchers, actresses, etc.  That gave me enough to start to get the rest.  I ended up 10  minutes over my average.  But that makes up for 15 min under my average yesterday.

Yes, this one was really, really hard!  But I think a Friday is supposed to be that.  I don't like the proper name clues, but at least they are easy to look up.  :o)

@Steve L 

“Recto” comes from Latin “rēctō,” the ablative of “rēctus,” meaning “straight” or “right.”

Me, I just remember R for R.

@Richard 

"Can't" works with third person singular as well as all the other persons, so "can't stand the heat" can clue WILT or WILTS equally well.  It's just one more example of the vagueness I talked about in my earlier post that is the hallmark of a late-week puzzle.  There's no best here.  The clue is fine.

But "DOESN'T stand the heat" is not an in-the-language phrase.  In other words, who says that?  So I don't think it's arguably better.

@Steve L 

If you can't stand the heat, WILT you get out of the kitchen?




Would the emus be able to take it?

@Lawillibug 

I suspect that you and the two people who recommended your comment did not really understand what Michael was saying...and he makes a good point.

You should reread Michael's post.

@Ed Actually I kind of liked a non-Andy Griffith clue for OPIE, and I learned a little something.

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wq9ewzSxFWU" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wq9ewzSxFWU</a>

"Andy Griffith named his character's son "Opie Taylor" on The Andy Griffith Show after Opie Cates, whom Griffith and producer Sheldon Leonard both liked."

@Andrew 

Thanks. 

I had never heard of TALC being added to rice and originally had sALt in my grid.

@Henrik 
METIER, ZINES, MOET, JEEZ not GEEZ, MYEYE for baloney?
Really?

@Chin

It’s actually PECOS Bill a legendary figure on the order of Paul Bunyan.









Are there any legendary emus?

@patk 

Your story just reminded me of selling programs as a student to tailgaters at Penn State football games in the 70s. The only way to get rid of your whole allotment was to target vehicles as they rapidly pulled in, in rows; milling about among tailgaters after that was too late (HITRATE too low)*. Competitive juices brought out vendors’ basic natures.  If you acted alone, or were too polite, obnoxious cutthroats would snipe your target from you. The best strategy would be to find a group of 4 or 5 willing to leap frog consistently with you, offering each a fair shot at a new arrival, and a de facto “union” to chastise away any snipers that tried to swoop in.

*although you could, occasionally, score a beer and/or a brat from a group of tailgating alumni

@Bob 
you list your location as CVNP!
Former Clevelander who, revisiting a couple weeks ago, spent a lovely morning hiking around old haunts therein--the Ledges, and Buttermilk Falls. New coffeehouse in Peninsula, I see. G.d, I miss that place!

@LBG 
I kept re-reading Gold's comment to find the grammar error.  Found it! 

While I enjoyed the 'Pi-Day' puzzle much more, I wouldn't call this puzzle the "worst".  I guess the creators can't please everyone!

@Steve L 
You eloquently state exactly how I felt about this puzzle, including starting at the bottom and triumphantly finishing at the top! 

In recent years I haven't finished every single Friday or Saturday puzzle, but I can appreciate how well-crafted this one was. (With the exception of MERER, that is!)

@Catherine 

As someone deeply familiar with the phrase “Put on blast”, I didn’t really get this one either. Back in my day (Chicago-area Black kid in the ‘90s), to put someone (or their business) on blast is to broadcast something (probably unflattering or incriminating) about them. 


It seems like the clue-writers instead think it’s synonymous with BASHing (insulting) someone, which is not quite right in my experience. Could be a regional/cultural difference tho.

@Mean Old Lady 
I've been trying to think of the poems I read and reread...one was about George Washington (in a book of collected 'American Heritage' versification/ speeches/anecdotes.)  ....and the other was about ?sunset?  

Around age 10 I wanted to write poems myself, having been steeped in John Greenleaf Whittier and Henry Wadsworth Longfellow....pretty sure none of mine rose to the level of doggerel.

@AABB 

I wouldn’t dare tell my wife that she looked rubicund.

“I swear, dear, it means rosy-cheeked!”

@WB 
I checked back over my decades, and it was a "Nope."


That goes for emus, too.

@Colby Hawkins 

I know that sense of BOP mainly from crossword puzzles. (For example, the 2/12/23 NYT puzzle.)

From the (mostly useless) Urban Dictionary, I see that it’s been around for at least 15 years.

@Joan 

An earlier comment noted that TALC is no longer added to white rice. 

But like you, I’m sticking with brown rice anyway.

@MmmmHmmm 

Have you signed up for the newsletter with the Easy Mode Friday clues? Maybe that would satisfy your wish for an easier puzzle. 

I’m a somewhat geeky Texan Who Likes Trivia with long ago roots in the northeast. I found today’s puzzle enjoyable and moderately challenging.

@Helen Wright 
I had no idea VIETNAM even produced coffee, let alone the second-most in the world. A trip to the atlas shows their climate to be tropical savanna, just like Brazil. I just assumed it was all tea over there.

Hand up for the dirty MARTINI...I use garlic-stuffed olives.

@John 
Same here. Finished it but not without hints from Deb.
Merer?

@Grant 

I belong to several Facebook groups for crossword constructors. From what I've read, for many years now, the NYT editors have typically changed about half the constructor's clues (maybe more than half for less experienced constructors).

And I saw a video several years ago in which Will Shortz and Joel Fagliano discussed clues. They said that unless they agreed that the constructor's clue was good, they would change it.

@Mojo 

I’ve reached the age where every movie or song I think of as being 10 years old turns out to be 20. 



>>>

@Mortiser 

It’s slang that’s been around for at least 15 years. 

I know it only from previous crossword puzzles.

@Smam,

How would that be a selfie if your friend took it?

If anyone could claim it was a selfie, it might be your friend (and you photobombed it). But it definitely cannot be SELFIE.

@Barry Ancona
See the Tricky Clues section of Wordplay.
It’s a clever clue either way.

@Andrew 
Since talc can contain naturally occurring asbestos, I'm relieved to hear it is no longer added to rice.

..................................................

@Kris T 

I typed “PHYLLISWHEATLY instead of PHILLIS…

That made SHILOH into SHYLOH, an obvious mistake I didn’t notice until I got the “close but no cigar screen.”  There was nothing shy about the Battle of Shiloh.

@Dave S 
I don’t get the email from Wordplay that you refer to, so I wasn’t sure what you meant . Easy to track down, though. Anyone who has done today’s Wordle already, or who doesn’t care about spoilers, you should check this out. “What on earth were you thinking?” is a gross understatement. Check out:

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/4ywd8zct" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/4ywd8zct</a>

@Michael soni?

“ … the first ten minutes, so I stopped.”

My apologies, 2024 and apple can’t replicate Word 98’s spell check.

@Christopher 

“By the end of the day, a mere dozen commenters had questioned the spelling of JEEZ. MERER still was the number of commenters who noted that JEEZ is derived from ‘Jesus’.”

MERER is a word, albeit a rarely used and strange-looking one. And JEEZ is certainly an acceptable (and understandable) spelling.

@n 

1D is exactly what it says. From the Urban Dictionary, I gather it’s at least 15 years old. 

I have no idea what 1A is supposed to mean. I looked up BASH in the Urban Dictionary and learned a new meaning that doesn’t seem relevant.

@Melanie D. 

MY EYE and “Baloney” are old-fashioned ways of say “bull___.”



>>>

